        "user": "How does \"lexical reachability\" differ from vocabulary coverage?",
        "assistant": "Good question — these are genuinely different things, and the distinction is worth drawing carefully. I'll answer using your stipulated definition (with the caveat from my previous message that I'm treating it as a local construct, not established terminology).\n\n## Vocabulary Coverage\n\nA property of the **tokenizer / training corpus**:\n\n- Does the term exist as a token (or efficient subword decomposition) in the model's vocabulary?\n- Did the term appear with sufficient frequency in training data to acquire stable embeddings?\n- It's essentially a **static, pre-inference** property of the model artifact.\n- Binary-ish or frequency-based: \"the model has seen this word N times\" or \"this word tokenizes into K pieces.\"\n\n## Lexical Reachability (per your definition)\n\nA property of the **model's discriminative behavior** around a term:\n\n- Measures a *gap* (cold-state vs. post-definition distinguishability) — it's inherently **differential**.\n- Scored against **named near-neighbors**, so it's about *fine-grained discrimination*, not mere recognition.\n- Requires **in-context intervention** (the single-sentence definition) — it probes plasticity, not just prior knowledge.\n- Per-cell granularity (model × term × near-neighbor) — so a term can be \"reachable\" with respect to one neighbor and not another.\n\n## Key Differences\n\n| Dimension | Vocabulary Coverage | Lexical Reachability |\n|---|---|---|\n| What it measures | Presence/frequency in vocab or training | Discriminability shift after a definition |\n| Static or dynamic | Static (model artifact) | Dynamic (in-context, pre/post) |\n| Granularity | Per token | Per (model, term, neighbor) triple |\n| Comparative? | No — absolute property | Yes — gap-based |\n| Probes what | Prior exposure | In-context updatability against confusable alternatives |\n\n## The Conceptual Gap\n\nA term can have **full vocabulary coverage** but **low lexical reachability** — e.g., the model knows the token but can't reliably distinguish it from a near-neighbor even after being told the definition. Conversely, a term might tokenize into rare subwords (poor coverage) yet still be highly reachable if a single definition lets the model cleanly separate it from neighbors.\n\nSo vocabulary coverage asks *\"is the word in the model's repertoire?\"* while lexical reachability (as you define it) asks *\"how much does a brief definition close the discrimination gap against specifically-named confusables?\"*\n\nThe two could be empirically correlated but they're conceptually orthogonal: one is about substrate availability, the other about context-driven discriminative gain.",
